# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: doc-bushong
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:doc-bushong/1875-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1875 throughout the world.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The **1876 major league baseball season** was contested from April 22 through October 21, 1876, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the inaugural season of the National League and of Major League baseball.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Two non-NA teams would join as charter members, including the Cincinnati Reds (unrelated to the modern team) and Louisville Grays.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The 1876 schedule was formatted so that each team would play up to 10 games against each team in the league (split evenly between home and away games), for a maximum of 70 games (only fulfilled by the Boston Red Caps).
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Any game played against a team at home must be played within two months' time away, "under penalty of forfeiture." This was the only season that the National League adopted this format.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see a more regulated format, requiring teams to schedule 12 games against each team.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 22 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Athletics of Philadelphia.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 21, featuring a game between the Hartford Dark Blues and Boston Red Caps.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The first doubleheader in major league history occurred on September 9 between the Cincinnati Reds and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The year ended with the first postseason competition in major league history.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The contest featured the first and second-place regular season finishers.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Grays had three tie games.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues, New York Mutuals, and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues would play their final game at the Hartford Ball Club Grounds on September 16 against the St.
[src:doc-bushong/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings, relocating to Brooklyn, New York at the Union Grounds as the Brooklyn Hartfords for the start of the 1877 season.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The **1880 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 1, 1880, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the fifth season of the National League.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 season is known for the first two major league perfect games in history, as well as being the only perfect games in the 19th century.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Thrown by Lee Richmond and John Ward, these two perfect games were thrown in the span of five days, the shortest amount of time between two perfect games (the next closest is currently 20 days between Dallas Braden's May 9 and Roy Halladay's and May 29, 2010 perfect games).
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] A perfect game would not be seen again in the Major Leagues for 24 years when Cy Young threw his perfect game in 1904.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the Cincinnati Reds and Syracuse Stars disbanded, and were replaced by the Cincinnati Stars and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the Stars' only major league season.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the previous season and would be used until 1883.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 1, featuring a doubleheader between the Providence Grays and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Eight tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Stars, and Providence Grays had three tie games each.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, and Worcester Worcesters had two tie games each.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave the Putnam Grounds (where they played their inaugural seasons) and move to the Haymakers' Grounds, where they would play for two seasons through 1881.
[src:doc-bushong/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans begin to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing on September 11.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:doc-bushong/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:doc-bushong/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The **1884 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1884.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American Association's regular seasons ended on October 15, with the Providence Grays and New York Metropolitans as the NL and AA pennant winners, respectively.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The newly founded Union Association regular season ended on October 19, with the St.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the AA and NL began with Game 1 of the first World's Championship Series (the first inter-league championship game of its kind in the Major Leagues) on October 23 and ended with Game 3 on October 25, in what was a best-of-five-playoff.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Grays swept the Metropolitans in three games, capturing their first World's Championship Series.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the 1884 season, in September 1883, the Union Association was formed, in direct contravention to the reserve rule (that a ballplayer could be reserved by a team) of the 1883 National Agreement (a.k.a.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Tripartite Agreement) signed between the National League, American Association, and minor league Northwestern League.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] In response to formation of the UA, the AA expanded their league from an eight teams to twelve teams to undermine the weak footing the UA had, as UA teams were mostly in cities that already had established AA and NL teams.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The latter played their last game on August 2, and were replaced by the minor league Eastern League's Richmond Virginians to finish Washington's schedule.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Union Association was largely unstable throughout its only year in existence (though confidence in the league remained high), as three of its founding teams would not make it to the end of the season.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Altoona Mountain Citys folded on May 31, and were replaced by the Kansas City Cowboys on June 7.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Keystones folded on August 7, and were replaced by the Eastern League's Wilmington Quicksteps.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Browns relocated to Pittsburgh as the Pittsburgh Stogies following their August 21 game.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Quicksteps would fold on September 15, while the Stogies would fold just three days later.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] On September 27, the Milwaukee Brewers and St.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Paul Saints) were recruited from the Northwestern League to finish the Philadelphia / Wilmington and Chicago/Pittsburgh schedules, respectively.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 season featured the second African American player in the major leagues (following William Edward White five years prior), debuting May 1 and playing 42 games for the Toledo Blue Stockings of the American Association.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] During his tenure, he faced abuse from other players (including teammates), fans, and the press, and even threats of being mobbed by 75 men before a road trip to Richmond, Virginia, before being released due to injury on September 29, prior to the road trip.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] His brother Weldy Walker played on the Toledo Blue Stockings for five games between July and August, becoming the third African American in the major leagues.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 schedule consisted of 110 games for all teams in the American Association, which had twelve active teams, and 112 games for all teams in the National League and Union Association, each of which had eight active teams.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Each AA team was scheduled to play 10 games against the other eleven teams in their league, and each of NL & UA teams were scheduled to play 16 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League increased its total games per team from 98 to 112, 14 games to 16 games per seven opponents.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The new Union Association copied this format.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the American Association, expanding from eight to twelve teams, changed from the 98-game format to the 110-game format.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would continue to use their 112-game format through the following season, while the American Association would copy the NL format.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Union Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while American Association and National League Opening Days took place on May 1, featuring all twelve and all eight teams, respectively.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Union Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 19 featuring four teams, while the American Association and National League would see their final day of the regular season on October 15 featuring all twelve teams and four teams, respectively.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 World's Championship Series took place between October 23 and October 25.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Four teams played in four neutral or alternate sites in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] 35 tie games (19 in AA, 10 in NL, 6 in UA), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in *italics* indicates a team a player was on from a different league.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any stat from said different league is not calculated to determine the league leader.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Four of these teams folded, one of which relocated cities prior to folding.
[src:doc-bushong/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Hoosiers hosted 11 Sunday games at the Bruce Grounds north of Indianapolis city limits in Center Township on May 18, 25, June 22, 29, July 6, 13, 20, August 3, 10, 31, and September 21.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The **1885 major league baseball season** began on April 18, 1885.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the Chicago White Stockings and the St.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns as regular season champions of the National League and American Association, respectively.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the second World's Championship Series on October 14 and ended with Game 7 on October 24, in what was a best-of-seven-playoff.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The White Stockings and Browns ended the series in a disputed tie in seven games.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] This dispute was due to the Browns not considering their forfeit in Game 2 as a voided game, and as a result, claimed victory.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the 1885 season, the unstable single season Union Association disbanded.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Maroons of the Union Association joined the National League, in place of the disbanding Cleveland Blues.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The twelve-team American Association would contract down to eight teams, with the Columbus Buckeyes, Indianapolis Hoosiers, and Toledo Blue Stockings folding, while the late-entry Richmond Virginians returned to the Minor Leagues.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The National League's New York Gothams renamed as the New York Giants, and the American Association's Brooklyn Atlantics and Louisville Eclipse renamed as the Brooklyn Grays and Louisville Colonels, respectively.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The 1885 schedule consisted of 112 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the National League since the previous season.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association, due to downsizing from a twelve-team league to an eight-team league over the off season, took on this format.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the final season for this format, as the AA would implement a 140-game format and the NL a 126-game format the following season.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 18 featuring four teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 30, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and St.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 5 with a game between the Brooklyn Grays and Philadelphia Athletics, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 10, featuring four teams.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The 1885 World's Championship Series took place between October 14 and October 24, though was originally supposed to extend to October 31.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] Three teams hosted games at neutral sites, the Buffalo Bisons, Providence Grays, and St.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] 4 tie games (1 in AA, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Beaneaters, Chicago White Stockings, and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:doc-bushong/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings leave Lakefront Park (where they played for seven seasons) and move to West Side Park, where they would go on to play for seven seasons, partway through 1891.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Descended from the Colonial immigrant Bushong family, Albert John Bushong was born September 15, 1856, in Philadelphia, the son of Charles A.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Bushong attended public schools in Philadelphia and graduated from Central High School in 1876.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] After playing baseball in various minor league teams for a couple of years, he enrolled in 1878 in dental school at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Bushong was one of the first to matriculate in the brand-new Department of Dentistry and he received his D.D.S. in 1882.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] While attending dental school, he played professional baseball every year, catching in more than 230 games as well as "barnstorming" in the off-season with a different team, the Hop Bitters.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Bushong was the first University of Pennsylvania graduate to play in Major League baseball.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] He did not play ball for the university, as he was already playing pro-ball.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Gottery were married and together they had seven children.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] His baseball career, spanned from 1875 to 1891, and Bushong played on various professional minor league and major league teams, including the Brooklyn Atlantics (1875), Philadelphia Athletics (1876), Worcester Ruby Legs (1880–82), Cleveland Blues (1883–84), St.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Some believe his greatest success came in the latter part of his career, when Bushong played on five pennant winning teams and was in post-season play five times.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] His most notable performance is most likely with the 1886 St.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Louis Browns of the American Association when they beat the Chicago White Stockings of the National League, for the Championship (later called World Series).
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] For his part in the championship, in 1886, the Missouri Pacific Railroad, honored Bushong and several other players by renaming some of their whistle-stop towns.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] The town of *Weeks* in Kansas, became, *Bushong, Kansas*.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] In 1887 Bushong became one of the first baseball players to do paid product endorsements, in an advertisement for *Merrell's Penetrating Oil*, which was a cold medicine.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Leading up to the 1888 season, Bushong made news again, when Chris von der Ahe owner of the St.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Louis Browns sold the contracts for Bushong, along with pitcher "Parisian Bob" Caruthers, and first baseman/outfielder/pitcher Dave Foutz.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] The sale was to the Brooklyn Bride Grooms and their owner, Charlie Byrne who paid, what was then, the enormous sum of $19,000, for the trio.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] On July 4, 1889, in the second game of a doubleheader in St.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Louis, Bushong injured his arm and played in only two more games during the regular season.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] He never fully recovered from the injury, which marked the beginning of the end of his baseball career.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] The 1890 season, was Bushong's last on the Bridegrooms and in major league baseball and he was officially released on March 26, 1891.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Within a couple of weeks still wanting to play for the 1891 season, Bushong signed on with a minor league team and eventually played on two different teams through mid-July before he was released.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] In a game that was traditionally played bare-handed, it is difficult to say who was first to make and use the padded catcher's mitt similar to today's glove.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] The first player to wear a glove was catcher Doug Allison, in 1870.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] In 1888, Joe Gunson described his catcher's mitt, and is sometimes associated with its invention, along with Doc Bushong and others.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] But his claim as first is brought into question by a *Brooklyn Eagle* article that describes Bushong with his special glove at least a season before Gunson's claim.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] But on July 1, 1887, while at bat in the sixth inning of a game against Louisville, Bushong's fingers were mashed by a wild pitch from Louisville switch pitcher Ice Box Chamberlain The injury resulted in a broken finger and prevented him from playing for almost ten and a half weeks.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] But it is easy to believe that on September 18, 1887, when he returned, Bushong had seriously padded a mitt to protect his hand as well his dentistry profession.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Further, an article on October 13, 1887, by the Brooklyn Eagle, tells of Bushong losing his *old glove.*...
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] The photographs taken of Bushong, used for the 1888 season, on the Old Judge baseball cards, show him with thick gloves on *both* hands, but in 1889 Sporting Life magazine described his mitt as a *spring mattress on his left hand.*.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] In the end, most agree that Bushong certainly deserves credit in the evolution of the catcher's mitt and with his known motivation to protect his hands, many believe that *he* was its primary inventor.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] A minor scandal involving Bushong and the 1889 World Series came to light in November 1889.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Following the Bridegrooms' series loss to the New York Giants, six games to three, a telegram from Bushong to Giants catcher Jocko Milligan was revealed.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] The scheme involved a $400 prize to the individual winners of the series.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] The prize had been offered by a chewing gum firm, likely the Green and Blackwell Company of New York, known as *G and B Chewing Gum Co.*, who in 1888, were first to issue gum with their baseball cards.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Bushong's idea was *prize sharing*, where, before the actual games, they were to agree, whoever was the winner would split the prize with the loser.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] In the newspapers, it was briefly mentioned as cheating, even though the practice was common in numerous sports and had been around in baseball for over a decade.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Though embarrassed over the affair, nothing more came of it and Bushong continued playing.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Following his baseball retirement in 1891, Bushong, then 33 years old, began practicing dentistry full-time along with two brothers, who were also dentists, at a large dental house in Hoboken, New Jersey.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Eventually he became manager of the establishment.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Also while working in Hoboken, he began and, according to baseball historian William Rankin, "built up a large and flourishing practice", at his home in south Brooklyn, 442 Ninth Street.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] On November 9, 1898, Bushong's 4-year-old son died after being severely burned in an election night bonfire, which were common ritual at the time.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] Eventually three of his sons, as well as a nephew, also became Brooklyn dentists and several worked at the Bushong family business, which was in operation as late as 1942.
[src:doc-bushong/doc-bushong] On August 19, 1908, Albert John Bushong died of cancer at his home, 442 Ninth Street, Brooklyn, at the age of 51 and was buried in the Holy Cross Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
